Previous model comparison

fy18_prb <- predict(gam_final_18, newdata = new.modeling.data, type = 'response') %>% as.numeric()
fy18_amt <- predict(lm_final_18, newdata = new.modeling.data, type = 'response')
# FY18 data max EV score (PR)
idx <- which(new.modeling.data$ID_NUMBER == '0000372980')
data.frame(
  p18 = fy18_prb[idx]
  , p19 = preds_prb[idx]
  , g18 = fy18_amt[idx]
  , g19 = preds_amt[idx]
) %>% mutate(
  ev18 = p18 * g18
  , ev19 = p19 * g19
)

Interestingly, the amount models are pretty close but the probabilities are very different.

LM comparison

coef18_lm <- summary(lm_final_18)$coef %>% data.frame() %>%
  select(Estimate18 = Estimate, SE18 = Std..Error, Pr.t18 = Pr...t..)
coef19_lm <- summary(lm_final)$coef %>% data.frame() %>%
  select(Estimate19 = Estimate, SE19 = Std..Error, Pr.t19 = Pr...t..)
cbind(
  coef18_lm
  , coef19_lm
) %>% mutate(
  varname = rownames(coef18_lm)
  , delta = Estimate19 - Estimate18
  , delta_pct = {delta / abs(Estimate18)} %>% scales::percent()
) %>% select(
  varname
  , Estimate18
  , Estimate19
  , delta
  , delta_pct
  , SE18
  , SE19
  , Pr.t18
  , Pr.t19
) %>% mutate_if(
  is.numeric, signif, 3
)

GAM comparison

coef18_gam <- summary(gam_final_18)
coef19_gam <- summary(gam_final)
data.frame(
  names = coef18_gam$p.coeff %>% names()
  , coef18 = coef18_gam$p.coeff
  , coef19 = coef19_gam$p.coeff
) %>% mutate(
  delta = coef19 - coef18
  , delta_pct = {delta / abs(coef18)} %>% scales::percent()
  , t18 = coef18_gam$p.t
  , t19 = coef19_gam$p.t
)

There are some very wide swings in how certain variables, such as upgrade amounts, are treated. I’m thinking these should be handled differently in the future when I refit a new model.

coef1 model

  • Total giving during the out-of-sample time period was $97,525,891.
  • Those predicted to give at least $1,000 gave $92,902,087, or 95.3% of the total.
  • A total of 3253 donors were predicted to give at the $1,000 level and 1570 actually did, for a hit rate of 48.3%.
  • Average giving in this group is $28,558.90 per person.
  • This method elimintates 83321 entities, who gave a total of $4,623,804, or an average of $55.49 per person.

coef2 model

  • Total giving during the out-of-sample time period was $97,525,891.
  • Those predicted to give at least $1,000 gave $92,481,811, or 94.8% of the total.
  • A total of 2865 donors were predicted to give at the $1,000 level and 1531 actually did, for a hit rate of 53.4%.
  • Average giving in this group is $32,279.86 per person.
  • This method elimintates 83709 entities, who gave a total of $5,044,080, or an average of $60.26 per person.

coef1

  • Total giving during the out-of-sample time period was again $97,525,891.
  • Entities with a score of 1 or higher (6439 total) gave $91,907,963, or 94.2% of the total.

  • Average giving in this group is $14,273.64 per person.
  • This method elimintates 80135 entities, who gave a total of $5,617,928, or an average of $70.11 per person.

coef1

  • Of the 920 individuals with a relatively high predicted giving amount ($1,000) but a 0 expected value score, only 151 were actually donors (16.4%), giving a total of $2,510,973.

coef2

  • Of the 629 individuals with a relatively high predicted giving amount ($1,000) but a 0 expected value score, only 130 were actually donors (20.7%), giving a total of $3,031,271.

This compares favorably with last year’s results.

Conclusion: using the coef1 model results in “missing” fewer donors.

Save results

# Merged data frame
output_data <- data.frame(
  est.giving.coef1 = fy18_amt
  , est.p.coef1 = fy18_prb
) %>% mutate(
  ev.coef1 = est.giving.coef1 * est.p.coef1
  , est.giving.bin.coef1 = trunc(est.giving.coef1)
  , est.p.bin.coef1 = trunc(est.p.coef1 * 10)
  , ev.bin.coef1 = trunc(ev.coef1)
  , est.giving.coef2 = preds_amt
  , est.p.coef2 = preds_prb
  , ev.coef2 = est.giving.coef2 * est.p.coef2
  , est.giving.bin.coef2 = trunc(est.giving.coef2)
  , est.p.bin.coef2 = trunc(est.p.coef2 * 10)
  , ev.bin.coef2 = trunc(ev.coef2)
) %>% cbind(
  new.modeling.data
)
# Master data file
output_data %>% write.csv(
  file = 'data/2019-10-17 predictions.csv'
  , row.names = FALSE
)
# IDs and scores only
full.data %>% filter(
  # Exclude deceased
  RECORD_STATUS_CODE != 'D'
) %>% select(
  HOUSEHOLD_ID
  , ID_NUMBER
) %>% mutate(
  HOUSEHOLD_ID = HOUSEHOLD_ID %>% as.numeric()
) %>% left_join(
  output_data %>% mutate(
      HOUSEHOLD_ID = ID_NUMBER %>% as.numeric()
    ) %>%
    select(
      HOUSEHOLD_ID
      , est.giving.coef1
      , est.p.coef1
      , ev.coef1
      , est.giving.bin.coef1
      , est.p.bin.coef1
      , ev.bin.coef1
    ) 
  , by = c('HOUSEHOLD_ID')
) %>% write.csv(
  file = 'data/2019-10-17 export.csv'
